Cyberware.

Cyberware is machinery grafted into your own body. An installed implant
grants its bonuses, such as stats, resistances, or chance-based proc
effects, for as long as it stays inside you.

Every implant occupies one or more body locations: eyes, ears, brain,
skull, jaw, throat, neck, spine, heart, lungs, torso, skin, shoulders,
arms, hands, legs, and feet. Only one implant may occupy a location.

Implants also strain the body. Your strain limit starts at 6 and grows
with your level: one point per 10 levels, plus larger bonuses at levels
50, 100, 150, 200, and 250. Souls remorted through cyber-touched
origins gain 2 extra strain each, to a maximum of 10. You cannot
install an implant that would push your total strain past your limit,
and an implant may demand a minimum level or stranger things before
your body accepts it.

Commands:

cyberware
  Show your installed implants, occupied body locations, and strain.
  The command implants does the same thing.

cyberscan <implant>
  Inspect an implant's type, grade, body locations, strain, visibility,
  and proc count before installing it.

install <implant>
  Have a ripperdoc install an implant you are carrying.

extract <implant or location>
uninstall <implant or location>
  Have a ripperdoc remove an installed implant, returning it to your
  inventory.

Installation and extraction require a staffed ripperdoc clinic, and the
ripperdoc will not operate while you are fighting. The Forbidden Replacement
Table in Nethrys Undercity's Ripperdoc Quarter is a formal clinic. Cyberware
status and implant scans remain available anywhere. Use "engage ripperdoc"
at the clinic to review hardware, see the exact service fee, and confirm the
procedure.

Installation costs 10,000 coins per point of implant strain, with a 10,000
coin minimum. Extraction costs 5,000 coins per strain, with a 5,000 coin
minimum.

Installed implants cannot be dropped and stay with you across sessions.
Some implants are outwardly visible and anyone who looks at you will
see them; hidden ones stay your secret. Procs trigger on their own in
combat: on your hits, when you take damage, when you are badly hurt, or
when you make a kill, each with its own chance and cooldown.

